Introduction

It is more expensive to acquire new customers than sell more to an existing client. Customer churn is a fundamental problem and one of the most important concerns for companies. Due to its direct effect on companies’ revenues, many companies seek to develop means to predict potential customer churn and to detect factors that contribute to it so they can take necessary actions for its mitigation (Ahmad, Jafar, and Aljoumaa (2019)). Reducing customer churn can lead to increased profits, improved customer experience, optimized products and services, and higher customer retention (Kriti (2019)). The main contribution of my work is to gain a deeper understanding of my family business customer behavior and develop an accurate churn prediction model which assists the company in predicting customers who are most likely subject to churn. Moreover, I propose actionable plans to reduce churn by utilizing the two analyses above. Therefore, this study covers all four aspects of analytics: descriptive, diagnostic, predictive, and prescriptive.

Data Characteristics

The company manufactures four products: binders, lever arches, clipboards, and file boxes with many color and size variations. 90% of the company’s revenues come from lever arches, making it the top revenue-generating product for the company. The data is extracted directly from the company. A total of 12 datasets were collected, including six, each indicating company sales for an entire year from 2016 to 2021 for all the products and another six for the returned product sales for the six years. Each dataset is recorded by transactions, where each row indicates a purchase made by a customer. Each dataset contains 45 different variables that the company controls for. There are a total of 88683 entries of sales data and a total of 1362 entries of returns data in all six years, which already shows a meager return-to-sales ratio. All the values in each column are recorded in the Farsi language, and the dates are in Jalili format (Persian Calendar).

Data Manipulation and Transformation

From the list of 45 variables in sales and returned sales datasets, I identified and selected the variables that would help with my churn analyses, as shown below.

# Creating a function that selects desired variables, renames, and drops na's from the sales datasets.
sales_modify <- function (dataset) {
  dataset<-dataset %>%
    rename(Date = "تاريخ", 
           Units = "مقدار",
           Discount = "تخفيف",
           Product_Name= "نام كالا",
           Product_ID = "كد كالا",
           Unit_Price= "قيمت واحد",
           Total_Sales = "مبلغ كل",
           Customer_Name= "مشترى - تفصيلى شناور") %>%
    transmute(Date = as.Date(Date, "%Y/%m/%d"), Product_Name, Product_ID, Units, Unit_Price, 
              Discount, Customer_Name, Total_Sales) %>%
    drop_na()
  return(dataset)
}

# Creating a function that selects, renames, and drops na's from the returns datasets.
returns_modify<- function (dataset) {
  dataset<-dataset %>%
    dplyr::rename(Units_Returned = "مقدار",
           Product_Name= "نام كالا",
           Product_ID = "كد كالا",
           Customer_Name= "مشترى - تفصيلى شناور") %>%
    dplyr::transmute(Customer_Name, Product_Name, Product_ID, Units_Returned) %>%
    drop_na()
  return(dataset)
}

Next, I converted Jalili dates to Gregorian dates as shown below.

# A function that converts Jalali dates to Gregorian dates for each dataset.
dates_modify<- function (dataset) {
  # Seperating Year, Month, Day from Date column.
  Year<-format(dataset$Date, format = "%Y")
  Month <-format(dataset$Date, format = "%m")
  Day <-format(dataset$Date, format = "%d")
  # Initializing an empty date tibble.
  date_tibble <- tibble(
    Date = as.Date(character()))
  # Converting Jalali dates to Gregorian dates.
  i <- 1
  while (i<=nrow(dataset)){
    date_tibble<- add_row(date_tibble, Date = jal2greg(Year[i], Month[i], Day[i]))
    i=i+1
  }
  # Adding Gregorian dates to the dataset and removing Jalili Date column.
  dataset<-dplyr::select(dataset,-Date)
  dataset <- tibble(date_tibble, dataset) 
  #dataset <- select(dataset,-Date)
  return(dataset)
}

sales_2019 <- dates_modify(sales_1398)

The number of distinct product names resulted in more than 200 instances in the datasets; However, the company only manufactures four products: binders, lever arches, file boxes, and clipboards. This is caused by including the color and sizes of each product in their product name. The datasets do not have different variables to measure products’ color and dimensions, which is why color and size are included in their names. Additionally, the values do not have a uniform convention due to the lack of data validation during data entry. Therefore, the product name variable needs to be adjusted to only include four different products and not 200. Also, this project does the customer analyses only on lever arches as it generates the most revenue for the company. Hence, I filtered product names by lever arch to only include data on this product.

# Product name modified to have only 4 distinct product.
ProductNameModify<-function (dataset) {
  i<-1
  while (i<=nrow(dataset)){
    if (str_detect(dataset[i,2], "مقوا|چسب|جلد|كارت ليبل|كلاسور") && !str_detect(dataset[i,2], "تخته شاسى|قفل|جامجله اى")) {
      dataset[i,2]= "Binder"}
    else if (str_detect(dataset[i,2], "فيلتر|قفل|چفت")) {
      dataset[i,2]= "Lever Arch"}
    else if (str_detect(dataset[i,2], "جامجله اى|پاكت|پوشه|فولدر|كيف|كلر بوك|ديوايدر|ML 310|فايل باكس")) {
      dataset[i,2]= "FileBox"}
    else if (str_detect(dataset[i,2], "Lexi |پك ملزومات")){
      dataset[i,2]= "other"}
    else if (str_detect(dataset[i,2], "زير دستى|تخته شاسى")) {
      dataset[i,2]= "ClipBoard"}
    i=i+1
  }
  return(dataset)
}

Next, I created a variable called frequency that counts the number of times a customer purchased in a given year. I also aggregated each dataset with the total number of lever arch units purchased, maximum unit price purchased, total discounts received, and total sales of lever arches for each customer in a given year.

# calculating the frequency of purchases and converting to annual and aggregating the rest.
AnnualFrequeny<- function (dataset, year) {
  dataset<- dataset %>%
    group_by(Customer_Name) %>%
    summarise(frequency= n(), 
              Units = sum(Units),
              Unit_Price= max(Unit_Price),
              Discount= sum(Discount),
              Total_Sales= sum(Total_Sales)) %>%
    arrange(desc(frequency)) %>%
    mutate(Year = year)
  return(dataset)}


br_sales_2016<-AnnualFrequeny(br_sales_2016,2016)
br_sales_2017<-AnnualFrequeny(br_sales_2017,2017)
br_sales_2018<-AnnualFrequeny(br_sales_2018,2018)
br_sales_2019<-AnnualFrequeny(br_sales_2019,2019)
br_sales_2020<-AnnualFrequeny(br_sales_2020,2020)
br_sales_2021<-AnnualFrequeny(br_sales_2021,2021)

Below, I calculated the total units returned by each customer. Then I merged the returns data of a given year with the sales data of the same year and combined all six datasets to produce one dataset that includes all the years’ data. I also eliminated the missing values for when units and tot_units_returned values were missing. I corrected missing values produced in tot_units_returned by replacing each with a zero.

# calculating the total product returned by a costumer and then returns the merged data.
TotReturnedCalculate<- function (dataset1, dataset2) {
  dataset1<-dataset1 %>%
    group_by(Customer_Name) %>%
    summarise(tot_Units_Returned= sum(Units_Returned)) 
  merged_annual<- full_join(dataset1, dataset2, by = "Customer_Name")
  merged_annual<-select(merged_annual, c(Year, Customer_Name, Unit_Price, frequency, Units, tot_Units_Returned, Total_Sales, Discount))
  return(merged_annual)}
  
merged_2016<-TotReturnedCalculate(br_returns_2016,br_sales_2016)
merged_2017<-TotReturnedCalculate(br_returns_2017,br_sales_2017)
merged_2018<-TotReturnedCalculate(br_returns_2018,br_sales_2018)
merged_2019<-TotReturnedCalculate(br_returns_2019,br_sales_2019)
merged_2020<-TotReturnedCalculate(br_returns_2020,br_sales_2020)
merged_2021<-TotReturnedCalculate(br_returns_2021,br_sales_2021)

merged_2017<-merged_2017 %>%
  filter(!(is.na(Units) & !is.na(tot_Units_Returned)))
merged_2018<-merged_2018 %>%
  filter(!(is.na(Units) & !is.na(tot_Units_Returned)))

# merging all the rows of all 6 datasets to produce one dataset.
merged_data<-rbind(merged_2016,merged_2017,merged_2018,
                   merged_2019,merged_2020,merged_2021)

# replacing NA values with 0 for tot_Units_Returned variable.
merged_data<- merged_data %>%
  mutate(tot_Units_Returned= ifelse(is.na(tot_Units_Returned), 0, tot_Units_Returned))

Furthermore, significant corrections needed to be made for customers’ names. As a result of the inspection, some customers had “Mr.” and some did not, even though they were the same person. Another issue was extra spaces in their names, which did not match other instances of the same name. Additionally, some customers in the past have relegated their position to their children to operate. The customer name still needs to be the same in this case since the company has not changed. Similarly, when other people from the same company or store purchase, it should also count as the same customer. This transformation was the most challenging, and due to its complex nature, the corrections had to be done (for the most part) manually. I first took “Mr.” out of all the names, which helped solve some customers’ issues. For the rest of the names that needed to be fixed, I checked each name manually and looked to see if their last name matched any instances in the data. If it did, I checked their first names, if the first names did not match, then I contacted the company to check if they were related to the same company or store, and I corrected them accordingly. I used a similar technique for other cases as well. In total, 63 customer names were transformed out of 313 customers. Below, I show only a few customer name transformations to show some code.

The company produces lever arches of differing sizes—one in 7.5cm and another in 4.5cm, each with a different unit price. Due to the various costs of the two lever arch types, we need to aggregate unit price to the customer level because it will pose issues in predictive analytics. The analogy of the matter is like combining the prices of apples and oranges, which are not the same. To fix this issue, I transformed the unit price by taking the average unit price difference in percentage for both types of lever arches.

# Removing "Mr" from the beginning of the names to fix matching issues

merged_data$Customer_Name<-ifelse(str_detect(merged_data$Customer_Name, "بهزاد"), "بهزاد زيدى",merged_data$Customer_Name)

Exploratory Analysis

Independent Variables’ Performance Analysis

The graphs below show the performance of five of the predictors for lever arches. All the graphs show the annual sum of the values for returned sales, units sold, frequency, and discount. The annual number of customers was calculated by taking the group size. Overall, the frequency of customer purchases and the number of customers exhibit a downward trend from 2016 until 2019. However, the number of lever arches sold during the same period had an upward trend for the most part. This suggests that even though the company lost customers and the existing customers did not purchase as frequently, the remaining customers purchased significantly more significant quantities in the same period every year. Additionally, in 2018-2019 the company had the highest fall in frequency and number of customers, and during the same year, the units that were also sold sharply declined. Interestingly, the amount of returned products by customers in 2016 was significantly high, but between 2016 and 2019, it had a steep downward trend. This indicates that a major event in 2016 had a significant negative impact on customer purchasing behavior and satisfaction. However, the lever arch sales and customer behavior improved after 2019. Discount for most years shows 0 percent, which indicates that the company rarely gives a discount on their lever arches. The only year they gave a discount was in 2017 for about 5 percent on average, which increased their unit sales.

Customer Churn and Retention Rate

Customer churn rate is the percentage of a company’s total customers that stop doing business with the company over a specified period. When evaluated alongside other key customer retention metrics, churn rate is a powerful way to assess which product is doing well and where it needs improvement. A customer retention rate measures the rate a business has retained customers over time. The barplot and Table 2 below depict the customer churn from 2016 until 2020. Table 2 shows that, on average, the churn rate was around 30% throughout the six years, which is high. The highest churn rate was in 2017 at 37%, and the lowest churn was in 2019 at 27%. The graph shows that the most lever arch customers were gained in 2020, and the year with the least number of customers was 2019. However, in 2020, the company seems to have the highest customer churn. The barplot shows that the number of customers decreased from 2016 until 2019 and then sharply increased in 2020. Even though in 2020, the company had the highest number of customers, it did not do an excellent job at retaining them. Customer churn is an essential metric because lost customers equal lost revenue. If a company loses enough customers, it can seriously impact its bottom line. According to a Harvard Business School report, “increasing customer retention rates by 5% increases profits by 25% to 95%.” They found that existing customers are 50% more likely to try new products and spend 31% more on average than new customers. Hence, learning the cause of the high churn on lever arches and being able to control this in the future would significantly boost the company’s performance.

Customer Loyalty Analysis

Customer loyalty is choosing one company’s products and services consistently over its competitors. Customers who are loyal to one company aren’t easily swayed by price or availability. They would rather pay more and ensure the same quality service and product they know and love. Customer loyalty results from a company consistently meeting and exceeding customer expectations. Another study by Rare Consulting says that 83% of customers said their brand loyalty stemmed from trust. In other words, loyalty is about likability and the ability to trust the product and brand. Customers who trust the companies they do business with will be more likely to purchase again. When a customer is loyal to a company, they are more likely to repeat their business. They are also more likely to recommend products and services to others. The importance of customer loyalty impacts almost every metric important to running a business. Without satisfied customers that continue to buy, the company won’t survive. New customers tend to cost more to acquire and don’t spend as much money as loyal, repeat customers. Keeping customers coming back for more is critical to business success. And it’s why short-term profit is not a good strategy. Table 3 depicts the most loyal customers of lever arches. Over the six years, the company acquired 313 unique lever arch customers. Among 313 customers throughout the six years, 15 never churned and were customers for the longest time. From the 15 most loyal customers, the top 10 customers with the highest total purchases (after adjusting for returns), and the highest shopping frequency, are shown below. These customers are the company’s most valuable customers, and the company needs to pay special attention to maintaining their satisfaction.

Purchasing Frequency Rate Analysis

Purchase frequency is the number of times an average customer buys a good or service from a single seller in a given period. Purchase Frequency helps businesses understand their audience’s purchasing behavior and better structure their marketing activities around their customers’ habits. Table 5 depicts the annual average consumer purchasing frequency. The average purchase frequency throughout all six years is around 18, which means that each customer purchases lever arches 18 times per year. The lowest frequency was in 2019, with 13, and the highest was in 2021, at 22.7. The last couple of years had a significantly higher frequency with less variation, which is a good sign for the company.

Product Return Rate Analysis

Product return rate refers to the frequency that customers return their purchased product. It is calculated as the percentage of sales orders with a product return. The return rate is an important metric as it highly impacts customer satisfaction and revenue. Customers make returns for many reasons, such as damaged products, inaccurate descriptions, incorrect products, incorrect sizes, malfunctioning products, delayed delivery, or a change of mind. Table 6 shows the lever arch return rate for each year. Overall, the return rate is outstanding, with returns being close to zero. The highest return rate was in 2016 at 0.48%, and the lowest was in 2019.

Statistical Modeling

In this section, we train various Machine Learning models to predict the likelihood of a customer staying and continuing shopping binders for the following year. First, we split our dataset into train and test data. We will train our models using data from 2016 up to 2020 (excluding). Our test set includes only 2020 data. Since the dataset only goes up to 2021, we cannot determine whether users will continue to utilize the service in 2022. However, later in this section, the 2021 data will be used to predict out-of-sample data once we have developed an accurate model. Our dependent variable is Stayed, a classification that either takes “yes” if the customer stayed the following year and “no” otherwise. After analyzing the correlation coefficients of the previously selected independent variables, we eliminated those variables that were not significant. Therefore, the selected independent variables for model training with the highest significance are: log(frequency), Unit_Price, and num_years The Machine Learning models that are most relevant to customer churn prediction are: LogisticRegression, DecisionTree, RandomForest, SupportVectorMachines, XGBoost, and NaiveBayes Vafeiadis et al. (2015).

Baseline Model

The baseline model was calculated by finding which of the two classes (yes and no) occurred more in Stayed variable and assigned all the values as just that class. In this case, we had slightly more occurrences of yeses than nos. The baseline model performance predicted 65% of the values correctly. Baseline performance is solely to compare the performance of our more sophisticated models. And determine how much we have improved.

Logistic Regression

Our logistic model performs with 60% accuracy, which is a 5% decrease in accuracy compared to our baseline performance. Our Kappa is 0.2884, which is not great. Both Sensitivity : 0.9200 and Specificity : 0.4375. Our predictors for the model were frequency +log(Units) + Unit_Price+ num_years. The reason for choosing these predictors was because these predictors had the highest correlation coefficients and were statistically significant.

Conclusion

This paper aimed to predict my family’s business customer churn to improve the company’s sales performance and consumer retention. We gained valuable insights by analyzing and preparing the company’s data, producing visualizations, and building various forecasting models to predict the consumers’ churn. Additionally, we created a model with a 20 percent increase from the baseline performance, with Random Forest being our best-performing model at 85% accuracy on the test set. This model will give the company a better understanding of the company’s churn pattern and will improve business decisions. In the future, I plan to continue cleaning the data even more to improve my model accuracy. Second, I plan on doing the same analysis on the company’s second most revenue-generating product, binders. The final step in this project is to do prescriptive analytics of my family’s business. To provide intelligent recommendations for the optimal next steps for lowering customer churn on lever arches and binders to drive desired outcomes or accelerate results. Throughout the research, It became clear that the company had a high churn rate, which is problematic, but it had a reasonable revenue growth rate, frequency rate, and product return rate during the six years. Additionally, the number of years a customer has stayed was the most critical factor in our analysis; unit price and frequency of purchasing during the year also had a statistical significance. Therefore, to improve the company and lower churns, the company needs to pay special attention to these three factors and build actionable plans.
